During the 1960s, Brzezinski worked as an advisor to John F. Kennedy and then to the Lyndon B. Johnson administration.
He advised Carter on foreign policy during the 1976 election and then served as National Security Advisor (NSA) from 1977 to 1981, succeeding Henry Kissinger.
As national security adviser, he assisted Carter in the diplomatic handling of world affairs such as the 1978 Camp David Accords, the normalization of U.S.-China relations in the late 1970s, the Iranian Revolution that led to the 1979 Iran hostage crisis, and the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan in 1979.
