Not only does this confirm that at least some dinosaurs had feathers, a theory that is already widely accepted, but it also provides details that fossils generally cannot provide, such as color and three-dimensional arrangement.
Scientists say that the plumage of this animal was chestnut brown on the upper side and light or carotenoid colored on the underside.
The find also provides insights into the evolution of feathers in birds.
Because dinosaur feathers lack a well-developed shaft called a rachis, but do have other features of feathers - barbs and barbules - the researchers concluded that the rachis was probably a later evolutionary development than these other features.
The structure of the feathers suggests that they were not used for flight, but rather for temperature regulation or cardiac protection. The researchers suspected that although the sample was the tail of a young dinosaur, it showed the plumage of an adult and not the down of a chick.
The researchers claimed that although this is the tail of a young dinosaur, the sample shows adult plumage and not chick down.
